Regression Project: Boston House Price Prediction¶

Marks: 60¶

Welcome to the project on regression. We will use the Boston house price dataset for this project.

Objective¶

The problem at hand is to predict the housing prices of a town or a suburb based on the features of the locality provided to us. In the process, we need to identify the most important features affecting the price of the house. We need to employ techniques of data preprocessing and build a linear regression model that predicts the prices for the unseen data.

Dataset¶

Each record in the database describes a house in Boston suburb or town. The data was drawn from the Boston Standard Metropolitan Statistical Area (SMSA) in 1970. Detailed attribute information can be found below:

Attribute Information:

  • CRIM: Per capita crime rate by town
  • ZN: Proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq.ft.
  • INDUS: Proportion of non-retail business acres per town
  • CHAS: Charles River dummy variable (= 1 if tract bounds river; 0 otherwise)
  • NOX: Nitric Oxide concentration (parts per 10 million)
  • RM: The average number of rooms per dwelling
  • AGE: Proportion of owner-occupied units built before 1940
  • DIS: Weighted distances to five Boston employment centers
  • RAD: Index of accessibility to radial highways
  • TAX: Full-value property-tax rate per 10,000 dollars
  • PTRATIO: Pupil-teacher ratio by town
  • LSTAT: % lower status of the population
  • MEDV: Median value of owner-occupied homes in 1000 dollars

  • EDA is an important part of any project involving data.
  • It is important to investigate and understand the data better before building a model with it.
  • A few questions have been mentioned below which will help you approach the analysis in the right manner and generate insights from the data.
  • A thorough analysis of the data, in addition to the questions mentioned below, should be done.

Questions:

  1. What does the distribution of 'MEDV' look like?
  2. What can we infer form the correlation heatmap? Is there correlation between the dependent and independent variables?
  3. What are all the inferences that can be found by doing univariate analysis for different variables?
  4. Do bivariate analysis to visualize the relationship between the features having significant correlations (>= 0.7 or <= -0.7)

What does the distribution of 'MEDV' look like?¶

The distribution of 'MEDV' (Median value of owner-occupied homes in $1000) is skewed. Most of the houses have a median value in the range of $15,000 to $30,000, with a peak around $20,000. There are some high-valued houses around $50,000

What can we infer from the correlation heatmap? Is there correlation between the dependent and independent variables?¶

From the correlation heatmap, we can infer the following:

MEDV is negatively correlated with LSTAT (-0.74) and PTRATIO (-0.51). MEDV is positively correlated with RM (0.7) and ZN (0.36). Significant correlations (>= 0.7 or <= -0.7) between independent variables include: INDUS and NOX (0.76) INDUS and DIS (-0.71) RAD and TAX (0.91) NOX and AGE (0.73) NOX and DIS (-0.77)

What are all the inferences that can be found by doing univariate analysis for different variables?¶

CRIM: The distribution is highly right-skewed, indicating most areas have a low per capita crime rate, but a few areas have a very high crime rate.

ZN: Most of the data points are at 0, indicating many areas do not have large residential lots, but a few areas have a significant proportion of large residential lots.

INDUS: The distribution is bimodal, with peaks around 7.5 and 18, indicating areas with varying proportions of non-retail business acres.

CHAS: Most areas do not bound the Charles River (value 0).

NOX: The distribution is slightly right-skewed, with most areas having moderate NOX concentration levels.

RM: The distribution is approximately normal, centered around 6 rooms per dwelling.

AGE: The distribution is right-skewed, with many areas having older properties.

DIS: The distribution is right-skewed, indicating most areas have moderate to high distances from employment centers.

RAD: The distribution is highly right-skewed, with a significant number of areas having low accessibility to radial highways.

TAX: The distribution is bimodal, indicating varying property tax rates in different areas.

PTRATIO: The distribution has a peak around 20, indicating most areas have a pupil-teacher ratio around this value.

LSTAT: The distribution is right-skewed, indicating most areas have a moderate to low percentage of lower-status population.

MEDV: The distribution is right-skewed, with most houses having a median value in the range of $15,000 to $30,000.

In [127]:
correlation_matrix = boston.corr()
high_corr_var = np.where((correlation_matrix >= 0.7) | (correlation_matrix <= -0.7))
high_corr_var = [(correlation_matrix.columns[x], correlation_matrix.columns[y], correlation_matrix.iloc[x, y]) for x, y in zip(*high_corr_var) if x != y and x < y]

for var1, var2, corr_value in high_corr_var:
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    sns.scatterplot(x=boston[var1], y=boston[var2])
    plt.title(f'Bivariate Analysis of {var1} and {var2} (Correlation: {corr_value:.2f})')
    plt.xlabel(var1)
    plt.ylabel(var2)
    plt.show()

The analysis shows significant correlations between several features, indicating relationships that should be considered when building predictive models. Variables like NOX, AGE, and DIS show strong relationships with industrial activity and pollution, while LSTAT and RM are crucial in predicting home values.

linear_models = ['Linear Regression', 'Ridge Regression', 'Lasso Regression']

for model_name in linear_models:
    if model_name in models:
        model = models[model_name]  # Retrieving the model instance
        coefficients = model.coef_  # Getting the model coefficients
        intercept = model.intercept_  # Getting the model intercept
        features = X.columns  # Getting the feature names from the DataFrame

        # Creating a DataFrame with feature names and their corresponding coefficients
        coef_df = pd.DataFrame({
            'Feature': features,
            'Coefficient': coefficients
        })
        print()

        intercept_df = pd.DataFrame({
            'Feature': ['Intercept'],
            'Coefficient': [intercept]
        })
        print()
        coef_df = pd.concat([intercept_df, coef_df], ignore_index=True)

        print(f"Coefficients and Intercept ({model_name}):\n", coef_df)

Checking Linear Regression Assumptions¶

  • In order to make statistical inferences from a linear regression model, it is important to ensure that the assumptions of linear regression are satisfied.
In [139]:
# Fitting the model using statsmodels for detailed output
X_train_sm = sm.add_constant(X_train)  # Adding a constant term for the intercept
model_sm = sm.OLS(y_train, X_train_sm).fit()

# Printing the summary of the model
model_sm.summary()

# Prediction using the model
y_train_pred = model_sm.predict(X_train_sm)
residuals = y_train - y_train_pred

# Linearity
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.scatterplot(x=y_train_pred, y=residuals)
plt.axhline(0, color='red', linestyle='--')
plt.title('Residuals vs Fitted')
plt.xlabel('Fitted values')
plt.ylabel('Residuals')
plt.show()

# Normality of residuals
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.histplot(residuals, kde=True)
plt.title('Histogram of Residuals')
plt.xlabel('Residuals')
plt.ylabel('Frequency')
plt.show()

sm.qqplot(residuals, line='45', fit=True)
plt.title('Q-Q Plot of Residuals')
plt.show()

# Homoscedasticity
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.scatterplot(x=y_train_pred, y=np.sqrt(np.abs(residuals)))
plt.title('Scale-Location Plot')
plt.xlabel('Fitted values')
plt.ylabel('Sqrt( |Residuals| )')
plt.show()

# Independence
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.lineplot(x=np.arange(len(residuals)), y=residuals)
plt.title('Residuals vs Order of Data')
plt.xlabel('Order of data')
plt.ylabel('Residuals')
plt.show()

Residuals vs Fitted Values Plot:

The residuals are scattered randomly around the horizontal line (red line at zero), indicating that the linear relationship assumption holds true. There is no clear pattern in the residuals, which suggests that the model fits well and there is no major misspecification.

Histogram of Residuals:

The residuals follow an approximately normal distribution with a mean of zero, as indicated by the bell-shaped curve. This suggests that the normality assumption of the residuals is reasonably satisfied.

Q-Q Plot of Residuals:

The Q-Q plot shows that most of the residuals lie on the red line, indicating that the residuals are normally distributed.

Scale-Location Plot:

The spread of the residuals is roughly constant across all fitted values, indicating that the homoscedasticity assumption (constant variance of residuals) holds true. There are no clear patterns in the spread of the residuals.

Residuals vs Order of Data Plot:

The residuals appear to be randomly distributed with respect to the order of the data, suggesting that there is no autocorrelation. This supports the assumption of independence of residuals.

Recommendations:¶

Increase Rooms:

Encourage construction of homes with more rooms (RM) or renovation of existing homes to add additional rooms, as this is a significant positive predictor of home value.

Reduce Crime:

Implement crime prevention strategies such as hiring security guards to lower the crime rate (CRIM) in neighborhoods, thereby potentially increasing home values.

Community Upliftment:

Invest in community upliftment and social programs to reduce the proportion of lower-status population (LSTAT), as this will likely have a positive impact on home values.

Environmental Quality:

Focus on pollution control to reduce nitric oxide levels (NOX), especially in industrial areas, to improve residential desirability and property values. Infrastructure Development:

Improve road infrastructure to increase accessibility to radial highways (RAD), justifying higher property taxes (TAX) and supporting higher property values. Education:

Invest in educational quality improvements, particularly by reducing the pupil-teacher ratio (PTRATIO), to enhance the attractiveness of neighborhoods and boost property values.

These recommendations are aimed at addressing key factors that significantly impact property values, thereby supporting strategic urban planning and development initiatives.
